Getting Started

To begin using these scripts, you should have:

    A Linux environment or a terminal emulator
    Basic knowledge of command-line operations
    Bash installed (most Linux distributions come with bash pre-installed)

Clone this repository to your local machine:

git clone https://github.com/Yasser-Jemli/Linux_Training_1.git
cd Linux_Training_1

Script Descriptions
Script Name	Description
file_management.sh	Demonstrates file and directory operations (create, delete, copy, move)
networking_basics.sh	Covers basic networking commands such as ping, ifconfig, netstat, etc.
process_management.sh	Teaches process management commands like ps, top, kill, and how to control processes.
automation_tools.sh	Introduces automation with cron jobs, task scheduling, and creating automated backups.
text_processing.sh	Shows the use of grep, awk, sed, and other text manipulation commands.
system_monitoring.sh	Contains scripts for monitoring CPU usage, disk space, memory usage, and system logs.
Installation

Simply clone the repository, as no additional installation is required. Make sure each script has executable permissions:

chmod +x scriptname.sh

Usage

To run a script, use the following command format:

./scriptname.sh

For example, to run the file management script:

./file_management.sh

Each script includes comments and explanations to help you understand the steps.
Contributing

Feel free to contribute by adding new scripts or improving existing ones. To contribute:

    Fork the repository
    Create a feature branch (git checkout -b feature-branch)
    Commit your changes (git commit -m "Add new feature")
    Push to the branch (git push origin feature-branch)
    Open a pull request

